##Luxury cruise ships became the first overseas epidemic area in just 10 days

MICRO-SIGNAL YITIAOTV

Feature description, a short original video every day, every day to tell a moving story, every day selected human beauty, every day to live a better life with me.

One exclusive, original video per day

This is a ship that has no other ship,

The most hapless luxury cruise ship in history, the diamond princess.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen Risheng, the magician who performed aboard the diamond princess

On February 1st,

A Hong Kong passenger who had disembarked was found to have a new type of pneumonia,

From February 5th,

A total of 3,711 crew members and passengers were quarantined at sea,

As of 13 February,

A total of 218 people were diagnosed with new pneumonia,

Has become the worst "overseas epidemic area" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers are confined to their cabins,

Three meals are delivered to the door by the staff,

Each floor is rotated to the deck for 1.5 hours a day,

As the isolation time lengthened, the cruise ship environment became more and more hostile,

Some passengers haven't even changed their sheets for more than a week,

Food also changed from Western food into instant noodles and dry food.

There's a long line in the infirmary every day,

The number of people who can be screened,

But less than a tenth of the ship,

Crew and passengers

People are leaving messages or recording videos on the Internet asking for help:

"If you don't get infected, sooner or later you'll get infected,

Do you have to be diagnosed with new pneumonia to get off the ship?

Will I be next?"

But is it really better to get off the ship and see a doctor?

At least 30 confirmed American patients have been sent to Japanese hospitals,

Their response was:

It might be better to stay on the boat...

By Wenping Bai

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The eagerly awaited voyage to the sea changed key on January 25th. An 80-year-old Hong Kong passenger who became ill after disembarking from the ferry was confirmed to have new-type pneumonia by the Hong Kong government on February 1. On Feb. 3, the diamond princess scrambled back to Yokohama, Japan, before passengers knew what was happening.

The Japanese government decided to quickly screen all the people on board, but there were so many people on board that they could not be inspected at all. So on February 5, the Japanese government ordered a sea quarantine with immediate effect, much to the consternation of passengers who had packed their bags to get off the ship.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Many of the stranded tourists turned to the outside world for help via live broadcasts. One reached Chen Risheng, a magician who boarded a ship on the route. During the call, Chen Risheng's voice was hoarse and he coughed constantly, but he had no fever and could not be tested. You can only drink more water in the room, more rest... .

The following is Chen Risheng's statement.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Magician, who boarded the ship on January 27th with great anticipation, is now in quarantine

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen Risheng performs in a theater on a cruise ship, photo taken on January 29,2010

I am magician Chen Risheng, in charge of the magic show on the boat. On January 26, I flew from Taiwan to Vietnam to board the ship, but the day before, on January 25, when the ship docked in Hong Kong, a group of Hong Kong passengers disembarked, and we didn't even know anyone had been infected with new pneumonia. The trip went on as usual. On January 31, when the boat stopped at Port of Keelung, Taiwan, everyone got off the boat and went to play and eat.

Unexpectedly, on February 1, an 80-year-old passenger in Hong Kong tested positive for new pneumonia. I was supposed to pack up my stuff on February 3rd, but the last-minute notice from the ship was that no one could get off the ship and that they had to go through quarantine.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen Risheng living in the cabin is the exclusive performers of the single room

I live in a special room for the staff, simple furnishings, only a single bed, relatively small space, since the quarantine, I have not changed the sheets, but all the clothes are washed, I have detergent, anyway, the boat is very dry, it's washed, hung, dried the next day.

Every day on the ship, people from every floor are regularly arranged to go out on deck for 1.5 hours to let out air. The temperature in Yokohama is about 5 to 8 degrees. It's a bit cold. Last Saturday (February 8) , after I had lunch, I went to the deck for a walk. Everyone was required to wear a mask and blow on the sea breeze, it's really relaxing in the fresh air.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
That day, I met an 80-year-old Japanese mother-in-law, hobbling along on crutches, I suddenly sad, could not help crying, most of the ship is elderly, they are happy to play, but encountered a virus threat..

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The staff will regularly deliver food and water every day, will also be delivered sterile alcohol, masks, thermometers, passengers take their own temperature, a fever will be reported, priority screening, my temperature is 36.8 degrees, still normal.

I was anxious at first, and my biggest fear was that I would wake up every morning and see dozens more, 40 more a day, sixty more, and so on.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen posted a distress message on his website on February 1

On February 1st, I was so anxious that I posted a distress message on my website. But now that I'm paralyzed, I'm trying to adjust my mindset, telling myself to stay positive, to eat more fruit, to drink more water, to stay strong. The captain of the ship broadcasts a daily message encouraging the ship to go out to sea every two days, mainly to recycle the water and make sure there is enough water on board for use.

I have met a Japanese couple, among them, the husband was diagnosed with new type of pneumonia off the ship, but his wife has no symptoms, they live in the same room, there should be a high risk of infection, but because the wife has no fever, we'll have to continue quarantine on the ship for now.

The port of Yokohama is visible outside Chen's cabin and is guarded daily by the media

I have been more than 2 weeks since I got on the ship, anyway, those who are infected will be infected, get off the ship and go to treatment, there are ambulances waiting at the port, it is not infected by the resistance, willpower support it. Even if I did get infected, I don't think the symptoms would be too severe, treatable, the mortality rate wouldn't be too high, I think we should be positive.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chen Risheng asked his friends in Japan to help with the delivery of supplies

My acting job originally ran from January 27 to February 4, so I only packed for nine days. During the quarantine, I ran out of vitamin C, dietary supplement, snacks, and contact lenses. Fortunately, it is now open to ship supplies and medicine. I asked a friend to bring some necessities from Tokyo. He drove to Yokohama, the port staff will help deliver the supplies to the room, and I've only had them for three hours, very quickly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The worst-case scenario is continued quarantine, which currently means until February 19, but with new cases appearing every day, it's unclear whether the quarantine will be extended. It's hard for me to sleep at night because I haven't done anything all day and I can't sleep at night.

After this experience, when I was in the news events, will know the pressure, tension really is not outside the imagination of outsiders, I hope we can get through the difficulties safely home.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A luxury cruise ship becomes a quarantine

Let's take a look at the construction of this cruise ship.

The Diamond Princess, which operates under the American Princess Brand, is the largest of the Grand class.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Standard Cabin with balcony

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Cabin with windows

Of the 1,337 cabins, 748 have private balconies, 212 have enclosed windows, 29 are accessible and the remaining 348 are windowless inner cabins.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Facilities include bars, theatres, spas, swimming pools, casinos, art galleries, libraries, coffee shops, restaurants, laundries... And so on and so forth.

The long 16-day trip, which was affected by the new type of pneumonia, was a luxury trip from 250,000 yen (about 16,000 yuan) to 1.38 million yen (about 87,000 yuan) .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The quarantine is expected to end on February 19, and the cruise line has announced a full refund for the trip, but the company's share price has tumbled so badly that March and April cruises are almost impossible. The diamond princess was originally scheduled to make a short trip to Okinawa and other places after this trip. Now there is a wave of ticket refunds. Even if the whole ship is disinfected, it will not be able to reassure everyone in a short period of time.

Passengers have been shut off in their cabins for more than a week, cruise lines are offering free Wi-fi, many passengers are sharing their lives in isolation through the Internet, and some are asking for help.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hong Kong passenger "back row, back row" updates on the forum

The forum is open for questions

Visitors from Hong Kong, who go by the pseudonym "back row, back row" on the forum, answer questions and share updates from time to time. He mentioned that he and his family had gone out to play during the Spring Festival, and repeatedly stressed that "we are not biological weapons, we have done a good job of self-protection. " We hope that the outside world does not label the infected or quarantined.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The first day or two, passengers can not step out of the room at all, although the door is not locked, but as soon as they go out, will be immediately persuaded back to the room by the staff, "later arranged to take turns, 1.5 hours a day, feel like prisoners. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Hong Kong tourist said that food is now delivered to his room by workers wearing N95 masks. He can not choose meals. Although he can watch television, most of them watch Japanese NHK, while several Indian, Australian and CCTV stations have limited choices, "We were offered cards and board games. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sudoku and board games were distributed to relieve passengers'boredom

He worried, "do not know how to spread the virus, the ship is a confined space, stay in the room is not necessarily safe, the virus may also spread through the air conditioning bar. ". At the same time also shows that the mood has been relatively calm, occasionally clean the room, pay attention to personal hygiene, quietly until the end of 14 days of isolation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Australian passengers order wine online, and sellers fly drones to the diamond princess

Drone delivers red wine to make fun of misery

Dave and Jan, an Australian couple, placed an online order for wine on Feb. 7 and asked if the platform could deliver it to Japan free of charge. Within hours of receiving the order, the platform managed to send two cases of wine to the cruise ship via a drone.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At that time, although the port personnel found the drone, but did not stop, so the wine was delivered smoothly, the husband and wife were surprised to receive wine, immediately open the case, send photos, enjoy the happy time.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Japanese Internet User Coco's parents quarantined on cruise ship

The parents are quarantined on the ship to let everyone know they're safe

Japanese born Coco, whose parents took the cruise, doesn't get on but tweets daily updates about her parents. She said her mother, who was originally a bright person, was depressed after being isolated.

Coco's parents didn't use social media, but because there was an internet connection on the ship, they ate and played lookout every day, contacting Coco. At first, the food was plentiful, but after nearly a week of isolation, the plates were too late to clean and the fresh ingredients too scarce, and gradually the dishes were replaced with disposable dishes, instant noodles and dry food.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The staff delivered breakfast at seven in the morning, lunch at two in the afternoon and dinner at seven in the evening. Coco's parents were very grateful to the staff. In addition to preparing meals, they also had to bear the emotions of the passengers, everyone's attitude is very sincere, and very kind, "I think most of the passengers can also cooperate with quarantine, mutual understanding. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers change their own sheets

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The ship's washing machines are out of service. Passengers clean their own clothes

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers take their own temperature every day, if there is a fever to notify the initiative

"My parents didn't have a balcony in the cabin, but they did have windows, two beds and a table, " Coco said. "They changed the sheets, did the laundry, did the occasional exercise, and looked after each other. I think it was lucky. Think about how anxious the passengers in the inner cabin would be without any sunshine. I hope a counselor could help them. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The staff asked for help en masse

The crew member, Binay Kumar Sarkar, from India, recorded a 90 second video and asked the Indian government for help in getting the Indian crew out of the ship.

Of the 1,045 crew members on board, 132 are Indian, living in cramped quarters, four share a bathroom, all eat together, live together, and bring meals into the cabin every day, it is a heavy physical and psychological burden for the staff.

"The diamond princess is like a small city. More than 10 people have been diagnosed with the new form of pneumonia, but before it is diagnosed, people eat together, move around together and work together, and there is no guarantee that it will not cause infection. "

As of February 14, two Indian sailors had been diagnosed with new pneumonia.

Slow flow of information on board

Some Japanese tourists say they have been fed up with the food on board these days, mostly foreign food, hoping to get some Japanese food, and they are grateful for the Miso Soup prepared on board the other day.

However, they also said that the biggest problem at present is that the flow of information is not perfect enough. Passengers have to be able to keep abreast of the latest situation through broadcasting, and sometimes the reception is not good outside the sea, and they can not receive outside information, even news that the Japanese government intended to disembark the passengers in groups came from relatives and friends.

"As time goes on and more cases are confirmed, it's really disturbing... "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Of the 218 confirmed cases, nearly 30 were American citizens who recorded their medical visits via video logs after they left the ship. Surprisingly, the consensus was that the hospital was worse off than the ship...

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 12, a 70-year-old American male passenger who was being taken off the ship with a diagnosis of new pneumonia was told by a phone call to get off the ship for medical treatment, but only the bare essentials were allowed. Packed up his backpack, the male passenger boarded a shuttle bus outside the ship and was taken to the waiting room 70 meters away.

Curtains were drawn on the shuttle bus while several patients with confirmed infection were waiting for departure.

"there were about a dozen confirmed patients coming off the ship. We were waiting in the waiting room. It was very cold and no one gave us any explanation in the hope of getting more information. " After a long wait of an hour and a half in the waiting room, the US passenger was taken in an ambulance with two other patients to a medical facility in Saitama Prefecture, Japan. It's a three-hour drive.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
American couple Kent and Rebecca, one of whom was diagnosed with pneumonia

Rebecca, 35, boarded the ship with her husband Kent, who was diagnosed with new pneumonia on February 7th. Kent, with whom she spends most of her time, is quarantined on the ship.

"I don't have obvious symptoms, but I do have a cough, and it takes me more than an hour to get to the hospital from the time I'm notified, " said Rebecca, who videotaped her daily visits to the doctor. She said that everything costs money in a Japanese hospital, even though there is a TV and a refrigerator in the ward, but none of the appliances worked, unless there was an extra credit card; there were no towels in the bathroom, and she was surprised to learn that "hospitals are worse off than boats. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Rebecca was observed in a ward at a Japanese hospital

The couple now skype daily, and Kent Says No one has disinfected their room since his wife got off the boat, and he thinks he will get the virus sooner or later. Separated, but still optimistic, Kent humorously brags to his wife about being stuck on a cruise ship and receiving a coke that will keep him happy all day.

Kent also said in the video that everyone on the ship now takes their own temperature every day and should be notified if something goes wrong, but he believed that it should be the staff who take the temperature, to prevent passengers from hiding their health for fear of worse treatment after disembarkation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On a cruise ship, the biggest anxiety for every passenger is, "will isolation really suppress the infection? Will I be the next to be diagnosed? " As the daily number of confirmed cases increased, so did the number of passengers in isolation rooms. The 3,711 people on the cruise ship became the most heavily infected outside mainland China, facing conditions including:

1. The ship is short of medical personnel. Passengers reported fever and wanted to see a doctor, but the infirmary was full, and sick passengers had to wait three hours for a doctor's appointment and, if deemed to be in a mild condition, continued to return to their rooms for quarantine.

2. Room sealed. The cabin air is not ventilated and dry, in addition to a few rooms with a balcony, more is not open the windows ventilated room, and even some people live in the lower floors of the cabin.

3. The room can not be cleaned every day. Staff suspended room service, passengers can only clean, replace the sheets, can not be disinfected.

4. The message is not getting through. Even though the captain broadcasts three times a day, the amount of information that can not be updated in a timely manner, coupled with the lack of steady signals on the cruise ship network, can not be kept up to date with the latest information from the cruise ship and the outside world, which is very worrying.

5. Language barrier. Most of the passengers on board were Japanese, as well as European and American tourists and people from Hong Kong and Taiwan. Communication was not easy.

6. Large consumption of standing stock. Most of the passengers are elderly people who need a large amount of drugs to lower blood pressure or blood sugar, which were originally used in preparation for the cruise, but are now being temporarily quarantined, together with the medicines needed by some foreign passengers, which are difficult to obtain in Japan, became the biggest problem.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
From February 11, the Japanese government formed an outbreak prevention team to board the ship to investigate and supply 500 people with medicine, medicine will be given priority to passengers with urgent needs or with serious diseases.

On Feb. 12, the announcement confirmed the diagnosis, as did a Japanese quarantine official who boarded the ship on Feb. 3 to hand out questionnaires, wearing a mask and gloves and suspected to have been infected without goggles and full body protective clothing.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 13, the Japanese government decided, on humanitarian grounds, to let elderly patients with other illnesses off the ship first, but the pressure is mounting as the number of cases of infection inside the ship increases.

With 120 million people in Japan, there are only 1,800 negative pressure isolation wards in the country, and with all the confirmed patients on board the cruise ships being treated in local hospitals, if there are more than 500 or even 1,000 confirmed patients in the future, it is bound to become a burden on Japanese health care, currently near Tokyo, Kanagawa Prefecture, Saitama, Chiba and other places, some hospitals have been stretched.

On February 14, the Japanese government, in the face of humanitarian considerations, arranged for an elderly person with underlying illness and in critical condition to disembark. An 85-year-old Taiwanese passenger coughing up blood, who shared a sealed cabin with his son, had several coughs that could not be tested for fever, the 85-year-old passenger finally got off the ship for treatment on the 14th. He was later diagnosed with a new type of pneumonia while his son remained isolated on the cruise ship.

More than half of the passengers on the diamond princess were over 60 years old, with diabetes, high blood pressure, weak immune systems, nutritional imbalances, and lack of exercise during isolation, elderly passengers in poor physical condition, if there is a slight symptom, it is best to be treated as soon as possible.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Offshore island-style" isolation, although to prevent the spread of the epidemic, but also attracted the global and some Japanese domestic doubts. Japan's shipping agent, Kazuki Guan, believes that the coastal isolation of ships was a response to the plague that Venice began to adopt in the 15th century, but nowadays, the human rights of the segregants are also a major concern for modern governments, if we isolate the crew, I'm afraid there's a risk of a mistrial.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The number of confirmed cases on the diamond princess is expected to continue to rise until the end of the quarantine period, as the passengers and crew have not landed in Japan, so who are the confirmed cases on the ship? At present, the Japanese government has proposed to the World Health Organization WHO, the cruise ship passenger cases are counted separately, but not included in Japan confirmed cases, so as not to cause the worsening of the epidemic in Japan, affecting the tourist economy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even though the Japanese government wants to carry out a large-scale quarantine of the entire ship as soon as possible, there are so many people on board that I am afraid it will not be completed before the end of the quarantine period, so I can only ensure the physical and mental health of the passengers first, so as to dispel the anxiety, medical Resources and living conditions on board should be enhanced as much as possible to ensure safe disembarkation of passengers and put an end to this maritime nightmare.

And that moment is five days away.
